 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| Popularity Award, Actor\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://m.chosun.com/news/article.amp.html?sname=news&contid=2015121101483 |title=MBC \uc5f0\uae30\ub300\uc0c1, \ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8 \ucee4\ud50c\uc0c1 \ud6c4\ubcf4 \uacf5\uac1c\u2026\ud669\uc815\uc74cvs\ud669\uc815\uc74c |date=11 December 2015 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Chosun |language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2019\n| 4th [[Asia Artist Awards]]\n| Best Icon Award in Television\n| rowspan=4|''[[My Fellow Citizens!]]''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news |url=http://m.star.mt.co.kr/view.html?no=2019112707085343476&ref= |work=StarNews |title=[\u2605\ud3ec\ud1a0]\ucd5c\uc2dc\uc6d0 '\ubc30\uc6b0\ub85c AAA\uc11c \ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8 \uc544\uc774\ucf58 \uc218\uc0c1' |date=27 November 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[2019 KBS Drama Awards|KBS Drama Awards]]\n| Excellence Award, Actor in a Mid-length Drama \n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://star.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/202001010044028007 |work=Hankook Ilbo |title=\uae40\uc9c0\uc11d,\ucd5c\uc2dc\uc6d0, \u2018KBS \uc5f0\uae30\ub300\uc0c1\u2019 \u7537\uc6b0\uc218\uc0c1... \u201c\uc288\ud37c\uc8fc\ub2c8\uc5b4\u00b7KBS \uac10\uc0ac\ud574\u201d |language=ko |date= 1 January 2020 |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Netizen Award, Actor\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| Best Couple Award <small>with [[Lee Yoo-young]]</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Super Junior}}\n{{SM Entertainment}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choi, Si-won}}\n[[Category:Super Junior-M members]]\n[[Category:Super Junior members]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean male idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean male singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean male film actors]]\n[[Category:South Korean male television actors]]\n[[Category:South Korean television presenters]]\n[[Category:South Korean radio presenters]]\n[[Category:South Korean Protestants]]\n[[Category:Inha University alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Seoul]]\n[[Category:Singers from Seoul]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean singers]]\n", "name_user": "Phily0501", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choi_Si-won"}
{"title_page": "Liver X receptor", "text_new": "{{infobox protein\n|Name=[[Liver X receptor alpha|LXR\u03b1 (nuclear receptor subfamily 1, group H, member 3)]]\n|caption=\n|image=\n|width=\n|HGNCid=7966\n|Symbol=NR1H3\n|AltSymbols=\n|EntrezGene=10062\n|OMIM=602423\n|RefSeq=NM_005693\n|UniProt=Q13133\n|PDB=\n|ECnumber=\n|Chromosome=\n|Arm=\n|Band=\n|LocusSupplementaryData=\n}}\n{{infobox protein\n|Name=[[Liver X receptor beta|LXR\u03b2 (nuclear receptor subfamily 1, group H, member 2)]]\n|caption=\n|image=\n|width=\n|HGNCid=7965\n|Symbol=NR1H2\n|AltSymbols=UNR\n|EntrezGene=7376\n|OMIM=600380\n|RefSeq=NM_007121\n|UniProt=P55055\n|PDB=\n|ECnumber=\n|Chromosome=\n|Arm=\n|Band=\n|LocusSupplementaryData=\n}}\n\nThe '''liver X receptor''' ('''LXR''') is a member of the [[nuclear receptor]] family of [[transcription factor]]s and is closely related to nuclear receptors such as the [[PPAR]]s, [[Farnesoid X receptor|FXR]] and [[Retinoid X receptor|RXR]].  Liver X receptors (LXRs) are important regulators of [[cholesterol]], [[fatty acid]], and [[glucose]] [[homeostasis]]. LXRs were earlier classified as [[Orphan receptor|orphan]] nuclear receptors, however, upon discovery of endogenous oxysterols as ligands, they were subsequently deorphanized.\n\nTwo [[isoforms]] of LXR have been identified and are referred to as '''[[liver X receptor alpha|LXR\u03b1]]''' and '''[[liver X receptor beta|LXR\u03b2]]'''.  The liver X receptors are classified into subfamily 1 ([[thyroid hormone receptor]]-like) of the [[nuclear receptor]] superfamily, and are given the nuclear receptor nomenclature symbols NR1H3 (LXR\u03b1) and NR1H2 (LXR\u03b2) respectively.\n\nLXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 were discovered separately between 1994-1995. LXR\u03b1 isoform was independently identified by two groups and initially named RLD-1<ref name=\"pmid7935418\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Apfel R, Benbrook D, Lernhardt E, Ortiz MA, Salbert G, Pfahl M | title = A novel orphan receptor specific for a subset of thyroid hormone-responsive elements and its interaction with the retinoid/thyroid hormone receptor subfamily | journal = Mol. Cell. Biol. | volume = 14 | issue = 10 | pages = 7025\u201335 |date=October 1994 | pmid = 7935418 | pmc = 359232 | doi = }}</ref> and LXR,<ref name=\"pmid7744246\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Willy PJ, Umesono K, Ong ES, Evans RM, Heyman RA, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = LXR, a nuclear receptor that defines a distinct retinoid response pathway | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 9 | issue = 9 | pages = 1033\u201345 |date=May 1995 | pmid = 7744246 | doi = 10.1101/gad.9.9.1033}}</ref> whereas four groups identified the LXR\u03b2 isoform and called it UR,<ref name=\"pmid7971966\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Ubiquitous receptor: a receptor that modulates gene activation by retinoic acid and thyroid hormone receptors | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 91 | issue = 23 | pages = 10809\u201313 |date=November 1994 | pmid = 7971966 | pmc = 45115 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.91.23.10809}}</ref> NER,<ref name=\"pmid7926814\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Shinar DM, Endo N, Rutledge SJ, Vogel R, Rodan GA, Schmidt A | title = NER, a new member of the gene family encoding the human steroid hormone nuclear receptor | journal = Gene | volume = 147 | issue = 2 | pages = 273\u20136 |date=September 1994 | pmid = 7926814 | doi = 10.1016/0378-1119(94)90080-9}}</ref> OR-1,<ref name=\"pmid7892230\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Teboul M, Enmark E, Li Q, Wikstr\u00f6m AC, Pelto-Huikko M, Gustafsson JA | title = OR-1, a member of the nuclear receptor superfamily that interacts with the 9-cis-retinoic acid receptor | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 92 | issue = 6 | pages = 2096\u2013100 |date=March 1995 | pmid = 7892230 | pmc = 42430 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.92.6.2096}}</ref> and RIP-15.<ref name=\"pmid7760852\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Seol W, Choi HS, Moore DD | title = Isolation of proteins that interact specifically with the retinoid X receptor: two novel orphan receptors | journal = Mol. Endocrinol. | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 72\u201385 |date=January 1995 | pmid = 7760852 | doi = 10.1210/mend.9.1.7760852}}</ref> The human LXR\u03b1 [[gene]] is located on [[chromosome 11]]p11.2, while the LXR\u03b2 [[gene]] is located on [[chromosome 19]]q13.3.\n\n==Expression==\nWhile the expression of LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 in various [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]] somewhat overlap, the tissue distribution pattern of these two isoforms overall differ considerably.  LXR\u03b1 expression is restricted to [[liver]], [[kidney]], [[intestine]], [[fat]] tissue, [[macrophages]], [[lung]], and [[spleen]] and is highest in [[liver]], hence the name liver X receptor \u03b1 (LXR\u03b1). LXR\u03b2 is expressed in almost all [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]] and [[organ (anatomy)|organs]], hence the early name UR (ubiquitous receptor).<ref name=\"pmid17372849\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chuu CP, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Modulation of liver X receptor signaling as novel therapy for prostate cancer | journal = J. Biomed. Sci. | volume = 14 | issue = 5 | pages = 543\u201353 |date=September 2007 | pmid = 17372849 | doi = 10.1007/s11373-007-9160-8 }}</ref> The different pattern of expression suggests that LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 have different roles in regulating physiological function.\n\n== Structure ==\n\nCrystal structure of human liver X receptor \u03b2(LXR\u03b2) forming heterodimer with its partner retinoid X receptor \u03b1(RXR\u03b1) on its cognate element, an AGGTCA direct repeat spaced by 4 nt shows an extended X-shaped arrangement, with DNA- and ligand-binding domains crossed, in contrast to the parallel domain arrangement of other NRs that bind an AGGTCA direct repeat spaced by 1 nt. The LXR\u03b2 core binds DNA via canonical contacts and auxiliary DNA contacts that enhance affinity for the response element.<ref name=\"pmid24561505\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lou X, Toresson G, Benod C, Suh JH, Philips KJ, Webb P, Gustafsson JA | title = Structure of the retinoid X receptor \u03b1-liver X receptor \u03b2 (RXR\u03b1-LXR\u03b2) heterodimer on DNA | journal = Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | volume = 21 | issue = 3 | pages = 277\u201381 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 24561505 | doi = 10.1038/nsmb.2778 }}</ref>\n\n== Activation/ligands ==\n\nLXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 form [[Protein dimer|heterodimer]]s with the obligate partner [[retinoid X receptor]] ([[Retinoid X receptor|RXR]]), which is activated by 9-cis-13,14-dihydroretinoic acid.<ref name=\"pmid26030625\">{{cite journal |vauthors=R\u00fchl R, de Lera AD, Krezel W | title = 9-cis-13,14-Dihydroretinoic Acid Is an Endogenous Retinoid Acting as RXR Ligand in Mice | journal = PLOS Genetics | volume = 11 | issue = 6 | pages = e1005213 |date= June 2015 | pmid = 26030625 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1005213| pmc = 4451509 }}</ref> The LXR/RXR heterodimer can be activated with either an LXR [[agonist]] (oxysterols) or a RXR [[agonist]] (9-cis-13,14-dihydroretinoic acid). Oxysterols, the oxygenated derivatives of [[cholesterol]], such as [[22R-Hydroxycholesterol|22(R)-hydroxycholesterol]], [[24(S)-hydroxycholesterol]], [[27-hydroxycholesterol]], and [[cholestenoic acid]], are the natural [[ligand]]s for LXR.<ref name=\"pmid8878485\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Janowski BA, Willy PJ, Devi TR, Falck JR, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = An oxysterol signalling pathway mediated by the nuclear receptor LXR alpha | journal = Nature | volume = 383 | issue = 6602 | pages = 728\u201331 |date=October 1996 | pmid = 8878485 | doi = 10.1038/383728a0 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9380679\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Forman BM, Ruan B, Chen J, Schroepfer GJ, Evans RM | title = The orphan nuclear receptor LXR\u03b1 is positively and negatively regulated by distinct products of mevalonate metabolism | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 94 | issue = 20 | pages = 10588\u201393 |date=September 1997 | pmid = 9380679 | pmc = 23411 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.94.20.10588}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9013544\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lehmann JM, Kliewer SA, Moore LB, Smith-Oliver TA, Oliver BB, Su JL, Sundseth SS, Winegar DA, Blanchard DE, Spencer TA, Willson TM | title = Activation of the nuclear receptor LXR by oxysterols defines a new hormone response pathway | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 272 | issue = 6 | pages = 3137\u201340 |date=February 1997 | pmid = 9013544 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.272.6.3137}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11089551\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Liao S | title = Cholestenoic acid is a naturally occurring ligand for liver X receptor alpha | journal = Endocrinology | volume = 141 | issue = 11 | pages = 4180\u20134 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11089551 | doi = 10.1210/en.141.11.4180}}</ref> After activation, LXR binds to LXR response element (LXRE), usually a variant of the idealized [[sequence]] AGGTCAN4AGGTCA, in the [[Promoter (biology)|promoters]] of LXRs' target [[genes]]. Some synthetic LXR [[agonists]] have been developed, including non[[steroid]]al LXR agonists T0901317<ref name=\"pmid11090131\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Schultz JR, Tu H, Luk A, Repa JJ, Medina JC, Li L, Schwendner S, Wang S, Thoolen M, Mangelsdorf DJ, Lustig KD, Shan B | title = Role of LXRs in control of lipogenesis | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 14 | issue = 22 | pages = 2831\u20138 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11090131 | pmc = 317060 | doi = 10.1101/gad.850400}}</ref> and GW3965.\n\n[[LXR-623]] ([[WAY 252623]]) CAS: [875787-07-8].\n\n== Target genes ==\n\nTarget [[genes]] of LXRs are involved in [[cholesterol]] and [[lipid]] [[metabolism]] regulation,<ref name=\"pmid12449021\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Edwards PA, Kennedy MA, Mak PA | title = LXRs; oxysterol-activated nuclear receptors that regulate genes controlling lipid homeostasis | journal = Vascul. Pharmacol. | volume = 38 | issue = 4 | pages = 249\u201356 |date=April 2002 | pmid = 12449021 | doi = 10.1016/S1537-1891(02)00175-1}}</ref> including:\n \n*  [[ATP Binding Cassette|ABC]] \u2013 '''A'''TP '''B'''inding '''C'''assette transporter isoforms [[ABCA1|A1]], [[ABCG1|G1]], [[ABCG5|G5]], and [[ABCG8|G8]]\n*  [[Apolipoprotein E|ApoE]] \u2013 '''Apo'''lipoprotein '''E'''\n*  [[cholesterylester transfer protein|CETP]] \u2013 '''C'''hol'''E'''sterylester '''T'''ransfer '''P'''rotein\n*  [[Fatty acid synthase|FAS]] \u2013 '''F'''atty '''A'''cid '''S'''ynthase\n*  [[CYP7A1]] \u2013 CYtochrome P450 isoform 7A1 - cholesterol 7\u03b1-hydroxylase\n*  [[Lipoprotein lipase|LPL]] \u2013 '''L'''ipo'''P'''rotein '''L'''ipase\n*  [[Liver X receptor alpha|LXR-\u03b1]] \u2013 '''L'''iver '''X''' '''R'''eceptor-'''\u03b1''' (a somewhat unusual example of receptor up-regulating its own expression)\n*  [[Sterol regulatory element binding protein|SREBP-1c]] \u2013 '''S'''terol '''R'''egulatory '''E'''lement '''B'''inding '''P'''rotein '''1c'''\n*  [[Carbohydrate regulatory element binding protein|ChREBP]] \u2013 '''C'''arbohydrate '''R'''egulatory '''E'''lement '''B'''inding '''P'''rotein\n\n== Role in metabolism ==\n\nThe importance of LXRs in physiological [[lipid]] and [[cholesterol]] [[metabolism]] suggests that they may influence the development of metabolic disorders such as [[hyperlipidemia]] and [[atherosclerosis]]. Evidence for this idea has been observed by recent studies that linked LXR activity to the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis. LXR\u03b1 [[knockout mice]] are healthy when fed with a low-[[cholesterol]] diet. However, LXR\u03b1 [[knockout mice]] develop enlarged fatty [[livers]], degeneration of [[liver]] cells, high [[cholesterol]] levels in [[liver]], and impaired [[liver]] function when fed a high-[[cholesterol]] diet.<ref name=\"pmid9630215\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Peet DJ, Turley SD, Ma W, Janowski BA, Lobaccaro JM, Hammer RE, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = Cholesterol and bile acid metabolism are impaired in mice lacking the nuclear oxysterol receptor LXR alpha | journal = Cell | volume = 93 | issue = 5 | pages = 693\u2013704 |date=May 1998 | pmid = 9630215 | doi = 10.1016/S0092-8674(00)81432-4}}</ref> LXR\u03b2 [[knockout mice]] are unaffected by a high-[[cholesterol]] diet, suggesting that LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 have separate roles. LXRs regulate [[fatty acid]] synthesis by modulating the expression of [[Sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1|sterol regulatory element binding protein-1c]] (SREBP-1c).<ref name=\"pmid11287605\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Yoshikawa T, Shimano H, Amemiya-Kudo M, Yahagi N, Hasty AH, Matsuzaka T, Okazaki H, Tamura Y, Iizuka Y, Ohashi K, Osuga J, Harada K, Gotoda T, Kimura S, Ishibashi S, Yamada N | title = Identification of Liver X Receptor-Retinoid X Receptor as an Activator of the Sterol Regulatory Element-Binding Protein 1c Gene Promoter | journal = Mol. Cell. Biol. | volume = 21 | issue = 9 | pages = 2991\u20133000 |date=May 2001 | pmid = 11287605 | pmc = 86928 | doi = 10.1128/MCB.21.9.2991-3000.2001 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11090130\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Repa JJ, Liang G, Ou J, Bashmakov Y, Lobaccaro JM, Shimomura I, Shan B, Brown MS, Goldstein JL, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = Regulation of mouse sterol regulatory element-binding protein-1c gene (SREBP-1c) by oxysterol receptors, LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 14 | issue = 22 | pages = 2819\u201330 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11090130 | pmc = 317055 | doi = 10.1101/gad.844900}}</ref> LXRs also regulate [[lipid]] [[homeostasis]] in the [[brain]]. LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 double [[knockout mice]] develop neurodegenerative changes in [[brain]] tissue.<ref name=\"pmid12368482\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang L, Schuster GU, Hultenby K, Zhang Q, Andersson S, Gustafsson JA | title = Liver X receptors in the central nervous system: From lipid homeostasis to neuronal degeneration | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 99 | issue = 21 | pages = 13878\u201383 |date=October 2002 | pmid = 12368482 | pmc = 129791 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.172510899 }}</ref> LXR\u03b2 [[knockout mice]] results in adult-onset [[motor neuron]] degeneration in male mice.<ref name=\"pmid15738425\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Andersson S, Gustafsson N, Warner M, Gustafsson JA | title = Inactivation of liver X receptor \u03b2 leads to adult-onset motor neuron degeneration in male mice | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 102 | issue = 10 | pages = 3857\u201362 |date=March 2005 | pmid = 15738425 | pmc = 553330 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0500634102 }}</ref>\n\n[[Adiponectin]] induces [[ABCA1]]-mediated [[reverse cholesterol transport]] by activation of [[Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma|PPAR-\u03b3]] and LXR\u03b1/\u03b2.<ref name=\"pmid31377319\">{{cite journal | vauthors=Hafiane A, Gasbarrino K, Daskalopoulou SS | title=The role of adiponectin in cholesterol efflux and HDL biogenesis and metabolism | journal= [[Metabolism: Clinical and Experimental]] | volume=100 | pages=153953 | year=2019 | doi = 10.1016/j.metabol.2019.153953 | pmid=31377319}}</ref>\n\n== Potential therapeutic applications of LXR agonists ==\n\nLXR [[agonists]] are effective for treatment of murine models of [[atherosclerosis]], [[diabetes]], anti-[[inflammation]], and [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Treatment with LXR [[agonist]]s (hypocholamide, T0901317, GW3965, or N,N-dimethyl-3beta-hydroxy-cholenamide (DMHCA)) lowers the [[cholesterol]] level in [[blood serum|serum]] and [[liver]] and inhibits the development of [[atherosclerosis]] in murine disease models.<ref name=\"pmid11238557\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Alberti S, Schuster G, Parini P, Feltkamp D, Diczfalusy U, Rudling M, Angelin B, Bj\u00f6rkhem I, Pettersson S, Gustafsson JA | title = Hepatic cholesterol metabolism and resistance to dietary cholesterol in LXR\u03b2-deficient mice | journal = J. Clin. Invest. | volume = 107 | issue = 5 | pages = 565\u201373 |date=March 2001 | pmid = 11238557 | pmc = 199420 | doi = 10.1172/JCI9794 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12032330\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Joseph SB, McKilligin E, Pei L, Watson MA, Collins AR, Laffitte BA, Chen M, Noh G, Goodman J, Hagger GN, Tran J, Tippin TK, Wang X, Lusis AJ, Hsueh WA, Law RE, Collins JL, Willson TM, Tontonoz P | title = Synthetic LXR ligand inhibits the development of atherosclerosis in mice | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 99 | issue = 11 | pages = 7604\u20139 |date=May 2002 | pmid = 12032330 | pmc = 124297 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.112059299 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11182136\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Auto-oxidized cholesterol sulfates are antagonistic ligands of liver X receptors: implications for the development and treatment of atherosclerosis | journal = Steroids | volume = 66 | issue = 6 | pages = 473\u20139 |date=June 2001 | pmid = 11182136 | doi = 10.1016/S0039-128X(00)00239-7}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18812595\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kratzer A, Buchebner M, Pfeifer T, Becker TM, Uray G, Miyazaki M, Miyazaki-Anzai S, Ebner B, Chandak PG, Kadam RS, Calayir E, Rathke N, Ahammer H, Radovic B, Trauner M, Hoefler G, Kompella UB, Fauler G, Levi M, Levak-Frank S, Kostner GM, Kratky D | title = Synthetic LXR agonist attenuates plaque formation in apoE-/- mice without inducing liver steatosis and hypertriglyceridemia | journal = J. Lipid Res. | volume = 50 | issue = 2 | pages = 312\u201326 |date=February 2009 | pmid = 18812595 | pmc = 2636920 | doi = 10.1194/jlr.M800376-JLR200 }}</ref> Synthetic LXR [[agonist]] GW3965 improves [[glucose]] tolerance in a murine model of diet-induced [[obesity]] and [[insulin]] resistance by regulating [[genes]] involved in [[glucose]] metabolism in [[liver]] and [[adipose]] tissue.<ref name=\"pmid12697904\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Laffitte BA, Chao LC, Li J, Walczak R, Hummasti S, Joseph SB, Castrillo A, Wilpitz DC, Mangelsdorf DJ, Collins JL, Saez E, Tontonoz P | title = Activation of liver X receptor improves glucose tolerance through coordinate regulation of glucose metabolism in liver and adipose tissue | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 100 | issue = 9 | pages = 5419\u201324 |date=April 2003 | pmid = 12697904 | pmc = 154360 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0830671100 }}</ref> GW3965 inhibits the expression of inflammatory mediators in cultured [[macrophage]] and [[inflammation]] in mice.<ref name=\"pmid12524534\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Joseph SB, Castrillo A, Laffitte BA, Mangelsdorf DJ, Tontonoz P | title = Reciprocal regulation of inflammation and lipid metabolism by liver X receptors | journal = Nat. Med. | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u20139 |date=February 2003 | pmid = 12524534 | doi = 10.1038/nm820 }}</ref> LXR agonists (T0901317, 22(R)-hydroxycholesterol, and 24(S)-hydroxycholesterol) were also shown to suppress the proliferation of [[prostate cancer]] and [[breast cancer]] cells<ref name=\"pmid15520170\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fukuchi J, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Chuu CP, Liao S | title = Antiproliferative effect of liver X receptor agonists on LNCaP human prostate cancer cells | journal = Cancer Res. | volume = 64 | issue = 21 | pages = 7686\u20139 |date=November 2004 | pmid = 15520170 | doi = 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-04-2332 }}</ref> as well as delay progression of [[prostate cancer]] from [[androgen]]-dependent status to [[androgen]]-independent status.<ref name=\"pmid16818617\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chuu CP, Hiipakka RA, Kokontis JM, Fukuchi J, Chen RY, Liao S | title = Inhibition of tumor growth and progression of LNCaP prostate cancer cells in athymic mice by androgen and liver X receptor agonist | journal = Cancer Res. | volume = 66 | issue = 13 | pages = 6482\u20136 |date=July 2006 | pmid = 16818617 | doi = 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-06-0632 }}</ref> Treatment with T0901317 decreases amyloidal beta production in an [[Alzheimer's disease]] mouse model.<ref name=\"pmid15557325\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Koldamova RP, Lefterov IM, Staufenbiel M, Wolfe D, Huang S, Glorioso JC, Walter M, Roth MG, Lazo JS | title = The liver X receptor ligand T0901317 decreases amyloid beta production in vitro and in a mouse model of Alzheimer's disease | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 280 | issue = 6 | pages = 4079\u201388 |date=February 2005 | pmid = 15557325 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M411420200 }}</ref> However, both T0901317 and GW3965 have been reported to increase [[Blood plasma|plasma]] and [[liver]] [[triglycerides]] in some mice models, indicating that T0901317 and GW3965 may not be a good candidate for a therapeutic agent. Developing new potent and effective LXR [[agonist]]s without the undesirable side effects may be beneficial for clinical usage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Im SS, Osborne TF | title = Liver x receptors in atherosclerosis and inflammation | journal = [[Circulation Research]] | volume = 108 | issue = 8 | pages = 996\u20131001 |date=April 2011 | pmid = 21493922 | url= https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.110.226878 | doi=10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.110.226878 | pmc = 3082200\n }}</ref>  In this regard, DMHCA was reported to reduce atherosclerosis in apolipoprotein E-deficient mice without inducing hypertriglyceridemia and liver steatosis.<ref name=\"pmid18812595\" /> When lipogenesis is increased by pharmacological activation of the liver X receptor, hepatic VLDL production is increased 2.5-fold, and the liver produces large TG-rich VLDL particles. Glucose induces expression of LXR target genes involved in cholesterol homeostasis like [[ABCA1]] which is defective in [[Tangier disease]]. A common feature of many metabolic pathways is their control by [[retinoid X receptor]] (RXR) heterodimers. LXR heterodimerises with RXR. Promiscuous RXR also heterodimerises with PPAR members. PPAR-\u03b1 plays a pivotal role in fatty acid catabolism in liver by upregulating the expression of numerous genes involved in mitochondrial fatty acid oxidation. Thus RXR is a common partner of two nuclear receptors acting in opposite directions with regard to fatty acid metabolism. So both LXR and PPAR-\u03b1 compete for the limited pool of RXR and this dynamic equilibrium determines the direction of lipid metabolism.<ref name = \"pmid18240340\">{{cite journal | author = Sanal MG | title = The blind men 'see' the elephant-the many faces of fatty liver disease | journal = World J. Gastroenterol. | volume = 14 | issue = 6 | pages = 831\u201344 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18240340 | doi = 10.3748/wjg.14.831| pmc = 2687050 }}</ref>\n\nThe hexacyclic aromatic ketones, (-)anthrabenzoxocinone and (-)bischloroanthrabenzoxocinone ((-)-BABX) derived from a ''Streptomyces sp.'' have micromolar affinity for LXR-\u03b1.<ref name=\"pmid16180833\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Herath KB, Jayasuriya H, Guan Z, Schulman M, Ruby C, Sharma N, MacNaul K, Menke JG, Kodali S, Galgoci A, Wang J, Singh SB | title = Anthrabenzoxocinones from Streptomyces sp. as liver X receptor ligands and antibacterial agents | journal = J. Nat. Prod. | volume = 68 | issue = 9 | pages = 1437\u201340 |date=September 2005 | pmid = 16180833 | doi = 10.1021/np050176k }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MeshName|liver+X+receptor}}\n*[http://nrresource.org] (Nuclear Receptor Resource).\n\n{{Transcription factors|g2}}\n{{Nuclear receptor ligands}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear receptors|1]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox protein\n|Name=[[Liver X receptor alpha|LXR\u03b1 (nuclear receptor subfamily 1, group H, member 3)]]\n|caption=\n|image=\n|width=\n|HGNCid=7966\n|Symbol=NR1H3\n|AltSymbols=\n|EntrezGene=10062\n|OMIM=602423\n|RefSeq=NM_005693\n|UniProt=Q13133\n|PDB=\n|ECnumber=\n|Chromosome=\n|Arm=\n|Band=\n|LocusSupplementaryData=\n}}\n{{infobox protein\n|Name=[[Liver X receptor beta|LXR\u03b2 (nuclear receptor subfamily 1, group H, member 2)]]\n|caption=\n|image=\n|width=\n|HGNCid=7965\n|Symbol=NR1H2\n|AltSymbols=UNR\n|EntrezGene=7376\n|OMIM=600380\n|RefSeq=NM_007121\n|UniProt=P55055\n|PDB=\n|ECnumber=\n|Chromosome=\n|Arm=\n|Band=\n|LocusSupplementaryData=\n}}\n\nThe '''liver X receptor''' ('''LXR''') is a member of the [[nuclear receptor]] family of [[transcription factor]]s and is closely related to nuclear receptors such as the [[PPAR]]s, [[Farnesoid X receptor|FXR]] and [[Retinoid X receptor|RXR]].  Liver X receptors (LXRs) are important regulators of [[cholesterol]], [[fatty acid]], and [[glucose]] [[homeostasis]]. LXRs were earlier classified as [[Orphan receptor|orphan]] nuclear receptors, however, upon discovery of endogenous oxysterols as ligands, they were subsequently deorphanized.\n\nTwo [[isoforms]] of LXR have been identified and are referred to as '''[[liver X receptor alpha|LXR\u03b1]]''' and '''[[liver X receptor beta|LXR\u03b2]]'''.  The liver X receptors are classified into subfamily 1 ([[thyroid hormone receptor]]-like) of the [[nuclear receptor]] superfamily, and are given the nuclear receptor nomenclature symbols NR1H3 (LXR\u03b1) and NR1H2 (LXR\u03b2) respectively.\n\nLXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 were discovered separately between 1994-1995. LXR\u03b1 isoform was independently identified by two groups and initially named RLD-1<ref name=\"pmid7935418\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Apfel R, Benbrook D, Lernhardt E, Ortiz MA, Salbert G, Pfahl M | title = A novel orphan receptor specific for a subset of thyroid hormone-responsive elements and its interaction with the retinoid/thyroid hormone receptor subfamily | journal = Mol. Cell. Biol. | volume = 14 | issue = 10 | pages = 7025\u201335 |date=October 1994 | pmid = 7935418 | pmc = 359232 | doi = }}</ref> and LXR,<ref name=\"pmid7744246\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Willy PJ, Umesono K, Ong ES, Evans RM, Heyman RA, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = LXR, a nuclear receptor that defines a distinct retinoid response pathway | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 9 | issue = 9 | pages = 1033\u201345 |date=May 1995 | pmid = 7744246 | doi = 10.1101/gad.9.9.1033}}</ref> whereas four groups identified the LXR\u03b2 isoform and called it UR,<ref name=\"pmid7971966\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Ubiquitous receptor: a receptor that modulates gene activation by retinoic acid and thyroid hormone receptors | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 91 | issue = 23 | pages = 10809\u201313 |date=November 1994 | pmid = 7971966 | pmc = 45115 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.91.23.10809}}</ref> NER,<ref name=\"pmid7926814\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Shinar DM, Endo N, Rutledge SJ, Vogel R, Rodan GA, Schmidt A | title = NER, a new member of the gene family encoding the human steroid hormone nuclear receptor | journal = Gene | volume = 147 | issue = 2 | pages = 273\u20136 |date=September 1994 | pmid = 7926814 | doi = 10.1016/0378-1119(94)90080-9}}</ref> OR-1,<ref name=\"pmid7892230\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Teboul M, Enmark E, Li Q, Wikstr\u00f6m AC, Pelto-Huikko M, Gustafsson JA | title = OR-1, a member of the nuclear receptor superfamily that interacts with the 9-cis-retinoic acid receptor | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 92 | issue = 6 | pages = 2096\u2013100 |date=March 1995 | pmid = 7892230 | pmc = 42430 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.92.6.2096}}</ref> and RIP-15.<ref name=\"pmid7760852\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Seol W, Choi HS, Moore DD | title = Isolation of proteins that interact specifically with the retinoid X receptor: two novel orphan receptors | journal = Mol. Endocrinol. | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 72\u201385 |date=January 1995 | pmid = 7760852 | doi = 10.1210/mend.9.1.7760852}}</ref> The human LXR\u03b1 [[gene]] is located on [[chromosome 11]]p11.2, while the LXR\u03b2 [[gene]] is located on [[chromosome 19]]q13.3.\n\n==Expression==\nWhile the expression of LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 in various [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]] somewhat overlap, the tissue distribution pattern of these two isoforms overall differ considerably.  LXR\u03b1 expression is restricted to [[liver]], [[kidney]], [[intestine]], [[fat]] tissue, [[macrophages]], [[lung]], and [[spleen]] and is highest in [[liver]], hence the name liver X receptor \u03b1 (LXR\u03b1). LXR\u03b2 is expressed in almost all [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]] and [[organ (anatomy)|organs]], hence the early name UR (ubiquitous receptor).<ref name=\"pmid17372849\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chuu CP, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Modulation of liver X receptor signaling as novel therapy for prostate cancer | journal = J. Biomed. Sci. | volume = 14 | issue = 5 | pages = 543\u201353 |date=September 2007 | pmid = 17372849 | doi = 10.1007/s11373-007-9160-8 }}</ref> The different pattern of expression suggests that LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 have different roles in regulating physiological function.\n\n== Structure ==\n\nCrystal structure of human liver X receptor \u03b2(LXR\u03b2) forming heterodimer with its partner retinoid X receptor \u03b1(RXR\u03b1) on its cognate element, an AGGTCA direct repeat spaced by 4 nt shows an extended X-shaped arrangement, with DNA- and ligand-binding domains crossed, in contrast to the parallel domain arrangement of other NRs that bind an AGGTCA direct repeat spaced by 1 nt. The LXR\u03b2 core binds DNA via canonical contacts and auxiliary DNA contacts that enhance affinity for the response element.<ref name=\"pmid24561505\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lou X, Toresson G, Benod C, Suh JH, Philips KJ, Webb P, Gustafsson JA | title = Structure of the retinoid X receptor \u03b1-liver X receptor \u03b2 (RXR\u03b1-LXR\u03b2) heterodimer on DNA | journal = Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | volume = 21 | issue = 3 | pages = 277\u201381 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 24561505 | doi = 10.1038/nsmb.2778 }}</ref>\n\n== Activation/ligands ==\n\nLXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 form [[Protein dimer|heterodimer]]s with the obligate partner [[retinoid X receptor]] ([[Retinoid X receptor|RXR]]), which is activated by 9-cis-13,14-dihydroretinoic acid.<ref name=\"pmid26030625\">{{cite journal |vauthors=R\u00fchl R, de Lera AD, Krezel W | title = 9-cis-13,14-Dihydroretinoic Acid Is an Endogenous Retinoid Acting as RXR Ligand in Mice | journal = PLOS Genetics | volume = 11 | issue = 6 | pages = e1005213 |date= June 2015 | pmid = 26030625 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1005213| pmc = 4451509 }}</ref> The LXR/RXR heterodimer can be activated with either an LXR [[agonist]] (oxysterols) or a RXR [[agonist]] (9-cis-13,14-dihydroretinoic acid). Oxysterols, the oxygenated derivatives of [[cholesterol]], such as [[22R-Hydroxycholesterol|22(R)-hydroxycholesterol]], [[24(S)-hydroxycholesterol]], [[27-hydroxycholesterol]], and [[cholestenoic acid]], are the natural [[ligand]]s for LXR.<ref name=\"pmid8878485\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Janowski BA, Willy PJ, Devi TR, Falck JR, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = An oxysterol signalling pathway mediated by the nuclear receptor LXR alpha | journal = Nature | volume = 383 | issue = 6602 | pages = 728\u201331 |date=October 1996 | pmid = 8878485 | doi = 10.1038/383728a0 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9380679\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Forman BM, Ruan B, Chen J, Schroepfer GJ, Evans RM | title = The orphan nuclear receptor LXR\u03b1 is positively and negatively regulated by distinct products of mevalonate metabolism | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 94 | issue = 20 | pages = 10588\u201393 |date=September 1997 | pmid = 9380679 | pmc = 23411 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.94.20.10588}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9013544\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lehmann JM, Kliewer SA, Moore LB, Smith-Oliver TA, Oliver BB, Su JL, Sundseth SS, Winegar DA, Blanchard DE, Spencer TA, Willson TM | title = Activation of the nuclear receptor LXR by oxysterols defines a new hormone response pathway | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 272 | issue = 6 | pages = 3137\u201340 |date=February 1997 | pmid = 9013544 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.272.6.3137}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11089551\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Liao S | title = Cholestenoic acid is a naturally occurring ligand for liver X receptor alpha | journal = Endocrinology | volume = 141 | issue = 11 | pages = 4180\u20134 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11089551 | doi = 10.1210/en.141.11.4180}}</ref> After activation, LXR binds to LXR response element (LXRE), usually a variant of the idealized [[sequence]] AGGTCAN4AGGTCA, in the [[Promoter (biology)|promoters]] of LXRs' target [[genes]]. Some synthetic LXR [[agonists]] have been developed, including non[[steroid]]al LXR agonists T0901317<ref name=\"pmid11090131\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Schultz JR, Tu H, Luk A, Repa JJ, Medina JC, Li L, Schwendner S, Wang S, Thoolen M, Mangelsdorf DJ, Lustig KD, Shan B | title = Role of LXRs in control of lipogenesis | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 14 | issue = 22 | pages = 2831\u20138 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11090131 | pmc = 317060 | doi = 10.1101/gad.850400}}</ref> and GW3965.\n\n[[LXR-623]] ([[WAY 252623]]) CAS: [875787-07-8].\n\n== Target genes ==\n\nTarget [[genes]] of LXRs are involved in [[cholesterol]] and [[lipid]] [[metabolism]] regulation,<ref name=\"pmid12449021\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Edwards PA, Kennedy MA, Mak PA | title = LXRs; oxysterol-activated nuclear receptors that regulate genes controlling lipid homeostasis | journal = Vascul. Pharmacol. | volume = 38 | issue = 4 | pages = 249\u201356 |date=April 2002 | pmid = 12449021 | doi = 10.1016/S1537-1891(02)00175-1}}</ref> including:\n \n*  [[ATP Binding Cassette|ABC]] \u2013 '''A'''TP '''B'''inding '''C'''assette transporter isoforms [[ABCA1|A1]], [[ABCG1|G1]], [[ABCG5|G5]], and [[ABCG8|G8]]\n*  [[Apolipoprotein E|ApoE]] \u2013 '''Apo'''lipoprotein '''E'''\n*  [[cholesterylester transfer protein|CETP]] \u2013 '''C'''hol'''E'''sterylester '''T'''ransfer '''P'''rotein\n*  [[Fatty acid synthase|FAS]] \u2013 '''F'''atty '''A'''cid '''S'''ynthase\n*  [[CYP7A1]] \u2013 CYtochrome P450 isoform 7A1 - cholesterol 7\u03b1-hydroxylase\n*  [[Lipoprotein lipase|LPL]] \u2013 '''L'''ipo'''P'''rotein '''L'''ipase\n*  [[Liver X receptor alpha|LXR-\u03b1]] \u2013 '''L'''iver '''X''' '''R'''eceptor-'''\u03b1''' (a somewhat unusual example of receptor up-regulating its own expression)\n*  [[Sterol regulatory element binding protein|SREBP-1c]] \u2013 '''S'''terol '''R'''egulatory '''E'''lement '''B'''inding '''P'''rotein '''1c'''\n*  [[Carbohydrate regulatory element binding protein|ChREBP]] \u2013 '''C'''arbohydrate '''R'''egulatory '''E'''lement '''B'''inding '''P'''rotein\n\n== Role in metabolism ==\n\nThe importance of LXRs in physiological [[lipid]] and [[cholesterol]] [[metabolism]] suggests that they may influence the development of metabolic disorders such as hyper lipidemia and [[atherosclerosis]]. Evidence for this idea has been observed by recent studies that linked LXR activity to the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis. LXR\u03b1 [[knockout mice]] are healthy when fed with a low-[[cholesterol]] diet. However, LXR\u03b1 [[knockout mice]] develop enlarged fatty [[livers]], degeneration of [[liver]] cells, high [[cholesterol]] levels in [[liver]], and impaired [[liver]] function when fed a high-[[cholesterol]] diet.<ref name=\"pmid9630215\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Peet DJ, Turley SD, Ma W, Janowski BA, Lobaccaro JM, Hammer RE, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = Cholesterol and bile acid metabolism are impaired in mice lacking the nuclear oxysterol receptor LXR alpha | journal = Cell | volume = 93 | issue = 5 | pages = 693\u2013704 |date=May 1998 | pmid = 9630215 | doi = 10.1016/S0092-8674(00)81432-4}}</ref> LXR\u03b2 [[knockout mice]] are unaffected by a high-[[cholesterol]] diet, suggesting that LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 have separate roles. LXRs regulate [[fatty acid]] synthesis by modulating the expression of [[Sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1|sterol regulatory element binding protein-1c]] (SREBP-1c).<ref name=\"pmid11287605\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Yoshikawa T, Shimano H, Amemiya-Kudo M, Yahagi N, Hasty AH, Matsuzaka T, Okazaki H, Tamura Y, Iizuka Y, Ohashi K, Osuga J, Harada K, Gotoda T, Kimura S, Ishibashi S, Yamada N | title = Identification of Liver X Receptor-Retinoid X Receptor as an Activator of the Sterol Regulatory Element-Binding Protein 1c Gene Promoter | journal = Mol. Cell. Biol. | volume = 21 | issue = 9 | pages = 2991\u20133000 |date=May 2001 | pmid = 11287605 | pmc = 86928 | doi = 10.1128/MCB.21.9.2991-3000.2001 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11090130\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Repa JJ, Liang G, Ou J, Bashmakov Y, Lobaccaro JM, Shimomura I, Shan B, Brown MS, Goldstein JL, Mangelsdorf DJ | title = Regulation of mouse sterol regulatory element-binding protein-1c gene (SREBP-1c) by oxysterol receptors, LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 | journal = Genes Dev. | volume = 14 | issue = 22 | pages = 2819\u201330 |date=November 2000 | pmid = 11090130 | pmc = 317055 | doi = 10.1101/gad.844900}}</ref> LXRs also regulate [[lipid]] [[homeostasis]] in the [[brain]]. LXR\u03b1 and LXR\u03b2 double [[knockout mice]] develop neurodegenerative changes in [[brain]] tissue.<ref name=\"pmid12368482\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang L, Schuster GU, Hultenby K, Zhang Q, Andersson S, Gustafsson JA | title = Liver X receptors in the central nervous system: From lipid homeostasis to neuronal degeneration | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 99 | issue = 21 | pages = 13878\u201383 |date=October 2002 | pmid = 12368482 | pmc = 129791 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.172510899 }}</ref> LXR\u03b2 [[knockout mice]] results in adult-onset [[motor neuron]] degeneration in male mice.<ref name=\"pmid15738425\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Andersson S, Gustafsson N, Warner M, Gustafsson JA | title = Inactivation of liver X receptor \u03b2 leads to adult-onset motor neuron degeneration in male mice | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 102 | issue = 10 | pages = 3857\u201362 |date=March 2005 | pmid = 15738425 | pmc = 553330 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0500634102 }}</ref>\n\n[[Adiponectin]] induces [[ABCA1]]-mediated [[reverse cholesterol transport]] by activation of [[Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma|PPAR-\u03b3]] and LXR\u03b1/\u03b2.<ref name=\"pmid31377319\">{{cite journal | vauthors=Hafiane A, Gasbarrino K, Daskalopoulou SS | title=The role of adiponectin in cholesterol efflux and HDL biogenesis and metabolism | journal= [[Metabolism: Clinical and Experimental]] | volume=100 | pages=153953 | year=2019 | doi = 10.1016/j.metabol.2019.153953 | pmid=31377319}}</ref>\n\n== Potential therapeutic applications of LXR agonists ==\n\nLXR [[agonists]] are effective for treatment of murine models of [[atherosclerosis]], [[diabetes]], anti-[[inflammation]], and [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Treatment with LXR [[agonist]]s (hypocholamide, T0901317, GW3965, or N,N-dimethyl-3beta-hydroxy-cholenamide (DMHCA)) lowers the [[cholesterol]] level in [[blood serum|serum]] and [[liver]] and inhibits the development of [[atherosclerosis]] in murine disease models.<ref name=\"pmid11238557\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Alberti S, Schuster G, Parini P, Feltkamp D, Diczfalusy U, Rudling M, Angelin B, Bj\u00f6rkhem I, Pettersson S, Gustafsson JA | title = Hepatic cholesterol metabolism and resistance to dietary cholesterol in LXR\u03b2-deficient mice | journal = J. Clin. Invest. | volume = 107 | issue = 5 | pages = 565\u201373 |date=March 2001 | pmid = 11238557 | pmc = 199420 | doi = 10.1172/JCI9794 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12032330\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Joseph SB, McKilligin E, Pei L, Watson MA, Collins AR, Laffitte BA, Chen M, Noh G, Goodman J, Hagger GN, Tran J, Tippin TK, Wang X, Lusis AJ, Hsueh WA, Law RE, Collins JL, Willson TM, Tontonoz P | title = Synthetic LXR ligand inhibits the development of atherosclerosis in mice | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 99 | issue = 11 | pages = 7604\u20139 |date=May 2002 | pmid = 12032330 | pmc = 124297 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.112059299 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11182136\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Song C, Hiipakka RA, Liao S | title = Auto-oxidized cholesterol sulfates are antagonistic ligands of liver X receptors: implications for the development and treatment of atherosclerosis | journal = Steroids | volume = 66 | issue = 6 | pages = 473\u20139 |date=June 2001 | pmid = 11182136 | doi = 10.1016/S0039-128X(00)00239-7}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18812595\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kratzer A, Buchebner M, Pfeifer T, Becker TM, Uray G, Miyazaki M, Miyazaki-Anzai S, Ebner B, Chandak PG, Kadam RS, Calayir E, Rathke N, Ahammer H, Radovic B, Trauner M, Hoefler G, Kompella UB, Fauler G, Levi M, Levak-Frank S, Kostner GM, Kratky D | title = Synthetic LXR agonist attenuates plaque formation in apoE-/- mice without inducing liver steatosis and hypertriglyceridemia | journal = J. Lipid Res. | volume = 50 | issue = 2 | pages = 312\u201326 |date=February 2009 | pmid = 18812595 | pmc = 2636920 | doi = 10.1194/jlr.M800376-JLR200 }}</ref> Synthetic LXR [[agonist]] GW3965 improves [[glucose]] tolerance in a murine model of diet-induced [[obesity]] and [[insulin]] resistance by regulating [[genes]] involved in [[glucose]] metabolism in [[liver]] and [[adipose]] tissue.<ref name=\"pmid12697904\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Laffitte BA, Chao LC, Li J, Walczak R, Hummasti S, Joseph SB, Castrillo A, Wilpitz DC, Mangelsdorf DJ, Collins JL, Saez E, Tontonoz P | title = Activation of liver X receptor improves glucose tolerance through coordinate regulation of glucose metabolism in liver and adipose tissue | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 100 | issue = 9 | pages = 5419\u201324 |date=April 2003 | pmid = 12697904 | pmc = 154360 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0830671100 }}</ref> GW3965 inhibits the expression of inflammatory mediators in cultured [[macrophage]] and [[inflammation]] in mice.<ref name=\"pmid12524534\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Joseph SB, Castrillo A, Laffitte BA, Mangelsdorf DJ, Tontonoz P | title = Reciprocal regulation of inflammation and lipid metabolism by liver X receptors | journal = Nat. Med. | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u20139 |date=February 2003 | pmid = 12524534 | doi = 10.1038/nm820 }}</ref> LXR agonists (T0901317, 22(R)-hydroxycholesterol, and 24(S)-hydroxycholesterol) were also shown to suppress the proliferation of [[prostate cancer]] and [[breast cancer]] cells<ref name=\"pmid15520170\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fukuchi J, Kokontis JM, Hiipakka RA, Chuu CP, Liao S | title = Antiproliferative effect of liver X receptor agonists on LNCaP human prostate cancer cells | journal = Cancer Res. | volume = 64 | issue = 21 | pages = 7686\u20139 |date=November 2004 | pmid = 15520170 | doi = 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-04-2332 }}</ref> as well as delay progression of [[prostate cancer]] from [[androgen]]-dependent status to [[androgen]]-independent status.<ref name=\"pmid16818617\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chuu CP, Hiipakka RA, Kokontis JM, Fukuchi J, Chen RY, Liao S | title = Inhibition of tumor growth and progression of LNCaP prostate cancer cells in athymic mice by androgen and liver X receptor agonist | journal = Cancer Res. | volume = 66 | issue = 13 | pages = 6482\u20136 |date=July 2006 | pmid = 16818617 | doi = 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-06-0632 }}</ref> Treatment with T0901317 decreases amyloidal beta production in an [[Alzheimer's disease]] mouse model.<ref name=\"pmid15557325\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Koldamova RP, Lefterov IM, Staufenbiel M, Wolfe D, Huang S, Glorioso JC, Walter M, Roth MG, Lazo JS | title = The liver X receptor ligand T0901317 decreases amyloid beta production in vitro and in a mouse model of Alzheimer's disease | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 280 | issue = 6 | pages = 4079\u201388 |date=February 2005 | pmid = 15557325 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M411420200 }}</ref> However, both T0901317 and GW3965 have been reported to increase [[Blood plasma|plasma]] and [[liver]] [[triglycerides]] in some mice models, indicating that T0901317 and GW3965 may not be a good candidate for a therapeutic agent. Developing new potent and effective LXR [[agonist]]s without the undesirable side effects may be beneficial for clinical usage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Im SS, Osborne TF | title = Liver x receptors in atherosclerosis and inflammation | journal = [[Circulation Research]] | volume = 108 | issue = 8 | pages = 996\u20131001 |date=April 2011 | pmid = 21493922 | url= https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.110.226878 | doi=10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.110.226878 | pmc = 3082200\n }}</ref>  In this regard, DMHCA was reported to reduce atherosclerosis in apolipoprotein E-deficient mice without inducing hypertriglyceridemia and liver steatosis.<ref name=\"pmid18812595\" /> When lipogenesis is increased by pharmacological activation of the liver X receptor, hepatic VLDL production is increased 2.5-fold, and the liver produces large TG-rich VLDL particles. Glucose induces expression of LXR target genes involved in cholesterol homeostasis like [[ABCA1]] which is defective in [[Tangier disease]]. A common feature of many metabolic pathways is their control by [[retinoid X receptor]] (RXR) heterodimers. LXR heterodimerises with RXR. Promiscuous RXR also heterodimerises with PPAR members. PPAR-\u03b1 plays a pivotal role in fatty acid catabolism in liver by upregulating the expression of numerous genes involved in mitochondrial fatty acid oxidation. Thus RXR is a common partner of two nuclear receptors acting in opposite directions with regard to fatty acid metabolism. So both LXR and PPAR-\u03b1 compete for the limited pool of RXR and this dynamic equilibrium determines the direction of lipid metabolism.<ref name = \"pmid18240340\">{{cite journal | author = Sanal MG | title = The blind men 'see' the elephant-the many faces of fatty liver disease | journal = World J. Gastroenterol. | volume = 14 | issue = 6 | pages = 831\u201344 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18240340 | doi = 10.3748/wjg.14.831| pmc = 2687050 }}</ref>\n\nThe hexacyclic aromatic ketones, (-)anthrabenzoxocinone and (-)bischloroanthrabenzoxocinone ((-)-BABX) derived from a ''Streptomyces sp.'' have micromolar affinity for LXR-\u03b1.<ref name=\"pmid16180833\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Herath KB, Jayasuriya H, Guan Z, Schulman M, Ruby C, Sharma N, MacNaul K, Menke JG, Kodali S, Galgoci A, Wang J, Singh SB | title = Anthrabenzoxocinones from Streptomyces sp. as liver X receptor ligands and antibacterial agents | journal = J. Nat. Prod. | volume = 68 | issue = 9 | pages = 1437\u201340 |date=September 2005 | pmid = 16180833 | doi = 10.1021/np050176k }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MeshName|liver+X+receptor}}\n*[http://nrresource.org] (Nuclear Receptor Resource).\n\n{{Transcription factors|g2}}\n{{Nuclear receptor ligands}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear receptors|1]]\n", "name_user": "Benbest", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRole in metabolism:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liver_X_receptor"}
